@hashemp206 ‚Äî thanks for asking.  With ASDK, item sizes are typically controlled by the ASDisplayNodes themselves (or ASCellNodes in this case).  There is a .preferredFrameSize property that you can set on certain elements, like ASImageNode, where they may not have a very clear size to calculate for themselves.

I hadn't considered this feature of the collection view layout, and will think about a way to detect and better document it (like printing a log to the console reminding people that layout size is driven by the elements).  There may also be a way to hook this up if the UICollectionView is notified of any changes to itemSize.

Note that one of the advantages of ASTableView and ASCollectionView is that they eliminate one of the two data source methods ‚Äî cellForRow/Item: and sizeForRow/Item: are collapsed into just nodeForRow/Item:.

Let me know if you have any difficulty here!  Usually creating an ASCellNode subclass is best, and from there you can override either:
- (ASLayoutSpec *)layoutSpecThatFits:(ASSizeRange)constrainedSize;
- (ASLayout *)calculateLayoutThatFits:(ASSizeRange)constrainedSize;

Documentation here:
