@lavoy Ah, yup, the placeholders are at fault here. We're going to discuss if there needs to be an internal solution, but what appears to be the problem is that since `ASTextNode` has a placeholder by default (check out the [placeholders example](https://github.com/facebook/AsyncDisplayKit/tree/master/examples/Placeholders)) and interacting with the element is triggering the display process, the placeholder is being added then instantly removed from the view.

My recommendation would be to set `placeholderEnabled = NO` on any text nodes that don't need placeholders. I did this on your sample project and it removed the flickering issue (check the [pull request](https://github.com/lavoy/ASTextProject/pull/1) I sent to your repo).

Thanks again for reporting this! Really good find.

@wockerwalker ‚Äî yes, we're planning changes to this behaviour in order to better handle large data sets (cc @rnystrom).  ASTableView and ASCollectionView currently blindly instantiate and measure _all_ available nodes as soon as they're available, but the "a node is never onscreen if it hasn't been measured" invariant can be preserved with incremental loading.  We're thinking of adapting the working range to only instantiate nodes when they're likely to be needed / destroy them as necessary for memory warnings.

For a stopgap measure, your suggestion of feeding ASTableView data in chunks ‚Äî tail-loading, √† la infinite scroll ‚Äî is your best bet.  It's possible to have your code execute closer to display time using, for example, `-displayWillStart`, but this may actually be detrimental depending on what you're trying to do.

Hope this helps!  =]

